  "bodyHtml": "<h2>Before the offer goes out</h2>\n<ul class=\"checklist\">\n  <li class=\"check\"><input type=\"checkbox\" id=\"hc1\"><label for=\"hc1\"><strong>Ask whether the candidate is bound by anything &mdash; and get the documents.</strong> Non-compete, non-solicit (customer and employee), confidentiality and invention-assignment agreements, plus any equity or bonus clawbacks. Candidates routinely underestimate what they signed. Read the actual paper, not the recollection.</label></li>\n  <li class=\"check\"><input type=\"checkbox\" id=\"hc2\"><label for=\"hc2\"><strong>Assess enforceability for this role, in this state.</strong> Whether a covenant binds turns on its scope, the employee&rsquo;s role, the consideration given, and the jurisdiction &mdash; and this is an area in real flux, with several states narrowing or banning non-competes and the federal picture unsettled. Confirm against the current rule rather than assuming the agreement is either ironclad or worthless. See <a href=\"restrictive-covenant-review.html\">Restrictive Covenant Review</a>.</label></li>\n  <li class=\"check\"><input type=\"checkbox\" id=\"hc3\"><label for=\"hc3\"><strong>Map the covenant to the job you are actually offering.</strong> Risk concentrates where the new role overlaps the old one &mdash; same customers, same territory, same product line, same team. A title change does not cure overlap; the work does.</label></li>\n  <li class=\"check\"><input type=\"checkbox\" id=\"hc4\"><label for=\"hc4\"><strong>Decide the risk question before you fall in love with the candidate.</strong> Some hires are worth a fight; some are worth a tailored role; a few are not worth the exposure at all. Make that call while you can still walk away, narrow the duties, or route it to counsel.</label></li>\n</ul>\n\n<h2>Set the rules in writing &mdash; before day one</h2>\n<p>Verbal instructions do not survive discovery. The clean-hands posture has to exist on paper, dated before the new hire has access to anything.</p>\n<ul class=\"checklist\">\n  <li class=\"check\"><input type=\"checkbox\" id=\"hc5\"><label for=\"hc5\"><strong>Instruct, in writing, not to bring or retain the former employer&rsquo;s information.</strong> No files, no customer or pricing lists, no source code, no decks, no contact databases &mdash; nothing physical or electronic, and nothing sitting in a personal email account, cloud drive, phone, or thumb drive. The rule is return or delete, not &ldquo;keep just in case.&rdquo;</label></li>\n  <li class=\"check\"><input type=\"checkbox\" id=\"hc6\"><label for=\"hc6\"><strong>Instruct not to use or disclose the former employer&rsquo;s confidential information &mdash; including from memory.</strong> General skill and experience travel with the employee; specific confidential and trade-secret information does not. Say so explicitly, so the line is the company&rsquo;s and not the new hire&rsquo;s to guess.</label></li>\n  <li class=\"check\"><input type=\"checkbox\" id=\"hc7\"><label for=\"hc7\"><strong>Instruct not to solicit in violation of a valid covenant.</strong> If an enforceable non-solicit covers customers or coworkers, the new hire stays off those names for its duration. Where a covenant is narrow or unenforceable, say what is permitted &mdash; silence invites the employee to guess wrong.</label></li>\n  <li class=\"check\"><input type=\"checkbox\" id=\"hc8\"><label for=\"hc8\"><strong>Tell the new hire not to recruit former colleagues on the company&rsquo;s behalf.</strong> A team &ldquo;lift-out&rdquo; is the fact pattern that turns a single departure into a coordinated-raid claim &mdash; and reframes the company from bystander to architect.</label></li>\n</ul>\n\n<h2>Shape the role to lower the exposure</h2>\n<ul class=\"checklist\">\n  <li class=\"check\"><input type=\"checkbox\" id=\"hc9\"><label for=\"hc9\"><strong>Tailor initial duties for high-risk hires.</strong> Where overlap is sharp, start the new hire on different accounts, a different territory, or non-competing work for an initial period. This both honors a valid covenant and undercuts an &ldquo;inevitable disclosure&rdquo; theory &mdash; the argument, recognized in some states and rejected in others, that the role cannot be performed without drawing on the former employer&rsquo;s secrets.</label></li>\n  <li class=\"check\"><input type=\"checkbox\" id=\"hc10\"><label for=\"hc10\"><strong>Wall off the obvious flashpoints.</strong> Keep the new hire out of decisions that turn on the competitor&rsquo;s confidential pricing, roadmap, or customer terms during any restricted period. Brief the hiring manager too &mdash; the casual ask to &ldquo;tell us what they were charging&rdquo; is what creates the problem.</label></li>\n</ul>\n\n<h2>Get the acknowledgment and document a clean start</h2>\n<ul class=\"checklist\">\n  <li class=\"check\"><input type=\"checkbox\" id=\"hc11\"><label for=\"hc11\"><strong>Obtain a written clean-hands representation.</strong> Have the new hire confirm they have returned all former-employer property, retained none of its confidential information, and will comply with any valid surviving obligations. This is protection for the company and a genuine reset for the employee.</label></li>\n  <li class=\"check\"><input type=\"checkbox\" id=\"hc12\"><label for=\"hc12\"><strong>Scrub the first-week intake.</strong> No forwarding of old work email, no uploading personal drives or contact exports, no &ldquo;starter&rdquo; templates carried over. Provision company devices and accounts clean. The first days generate the evidence either way.</label></li>\n  <li class=\"check\"><input type=\"checkbox\" id=\"hc13\"><label for=\"hc13\"><strong>Keep the onboarding record.</strong> The signed instructions, the representation, and the role description &mdash; dated and filed. If a letter arrives, the difference between a quick resolution and a costly one is often whether the file shows the rules were set up front.</label></li>\n</ul>\n\n<h2>Higher-risk situations</h2>\n<ul class=\"checklist\">\n  <li class=\"check\"><input type=\"checkbox\" id=\"hc14\"><label for=\"hc14\"><strong>Route close calls to counsel before extending the offer.</strong> An enforceable-looking covenant, a senior or customer-facing role, a direct competitor, or a multi-person move &mdash; any one of these is worth a privileged look before commitments are made.</label></li>\n  <li class=\"check\"><input type=\"checkbox\" id=\"hc15\"><label for=\"hc15\"><strong>Consider proactive notice to the former employer.</strong> In the right case, a measured letter &mdash; confirming the new hire&rsquo;s scope, that no confidential information was taken, and that any valid covenant will be honored &mdash; can set a cooperative tone and defuse a dispute before it forms. It is a judgment call: it also puts the other side on notice, so weigh it with counsel.</label></li>\n  <li class=\"check\"><input type=\"checkbox\" id=\"hc16\"><label for=\"hc16\"><strong>Have a forensic plan ready if a threat lands.</strong> Preserve devices and accounts, suspend deletion, and resist the instinct to &ldquo;just check&rdquo; what the new hire brought &mdash; that is for counsel and a neutral examiner to handle, not the manager.</label></li>\n</ul>\n\n<div class=\"callout\">\n  <span class=\"callout-label\">The thing behind the thing</span>\n  <p>Trade-secret suits against a new employer are almost always built from the new hire&rsquo;s own first-week emails and downloads &mdash; the forwarded contact list, the &ldquo;just my own files&rdquo; upload. The protection is to set the no-documents rule in writing before the start date, not to explain it after the complaint arrives.</p>\n</div>",
